ptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdrenal medulla\u003C/strong\u003E contains chromaffin cells which produce, store and release catecholamines (primarily adrenaline and noradrenaline). These cells are derived from neural crest cells during development.\u003C/p\u003E        \u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eadrenal cortex\u003C/strong\u003E contains different cell types that produce steroid hormones. The \u003Cstrong\u003Eanterior pituitary\u003C/strong\u003E contains various hormone-producing cells but not chromaffin cells. The \u003Cstrong\u003Ethyroid gland\u003C/strong\u003E contains follicular and parafollicular cells that produce thyroid hormones and calcitonin. The \u003Cstrong\u003Epancreatic islets\u003C/strong\u003E contain alpha, beta, delta and PP cells that produce various peptide hormones.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Chromaffin cells are neuroendocrine cells located in the adrenal medulla that produce catecholamines.","Chromaffin cells are derived from neural crest cells during embryological development."],"references":["Lotfi CFP, Kremer JL, Dos Santos Passaia B, Cavalcante IP. The human adrenal cortex: growth control and disorders. Clinics (Sao Paulo). 2018 Sep 6;73(suppl 1):e473s. doi: 10.6061/clinics/2018/e473s. PMID: 30208164; PMCID: PMC6113920","Melmed, S., Polonsky, K. S., Larsen, P. R., \u0026 Kronenberg, H. M. (2015). Williams textbook of endocrinology E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Clark, O. H., Duh, Q. Y., Kebebew, E., Gosnell, J. E., \u0026 Shen, W. T. (Eds.). (2016). Textbook of endocrine surgery. JP Medical Ltd","Young, W. F. (2011). Netter\u0027s Endocrine System: Netter Collection of Medical Illustrations: Endocrine System E-book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Wass, J. A., \u0026 Stewart, P. M. (Eds.). (2011). Oxford textbook of endocrinology and diabetes. Oxford University Press, USA"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"